sect1.para:
Depressive disorders
   Depressive disorders
 are among the most prevalent and burdensome mental health disorders, impacting an estimated 5% of the global population (World Health Organization (WHO), 
   2023
). At the individual level, depressive disorders are a source of emotional distress and represent the leading cause of disability by accounting for 6.2% of all years lived with a disability (WHO, 
   2020
). Depressive disorders are also associated with higher suicide risk (Chesney et al., 
   2014
) and lower quality of life (Rapaport et al., 
   2005
). In the broader context, depressive disorders create significant emotional distress and economic burden for families, interpersonal relationships, and society at large. This impact spans across all ages, geographical, racial, ethnic, and socioeconomic groups, and alarmingly, the lifetime and current rate of depressive disorders has increased over the past several years (Santomauro et al., 
   2021
). Given the costs and risks associated with depressive disorders, it is crucial that mental health providers have a comprehensive understanding of diagnostic criteria, evidence-based assessment methods, and cultural considerations for managing depressive disorders.
